data.content:
The parameters to `Assert.AreEqual` are swapped. The signature is `AreEqual(expected, actual)`, but your code passes `(actual, expected)`. This causes confusing failure messages — e.g., "Expected: \<result\> Actual: \<5\>" instead of the reverse.

**Fix:**

```csharp
// Before (wrong order)
Assert.AreEqual(result, 5);
Assert.AreEqual(result, 0);

// After (correct order)
Assert.AreEqual(5, result);
Assert.AreEqual(0, result);
```

This is one of the most common MSTest pitfalls. The first argument is always the **expected** value (the literal/constant), and the second is the **actual** value (what your code produced).
